    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f6536d04-b4c9-4b20-935c-0d27759bf120",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old Czech woman with a slim, slightly pale appearance who presents to the oncology outpatient clinic in Prague. She reports a several-month history of intermittent lower abdominal cramping, unexplained weight loss of approximately 6 kg over the past four months, and episodes of rectal bleeding mixed with stool. She has also noticed increasing fatigue and occasional dizziness on exertion. On examination she appears fatigued and mildly anaemic, with conjunctival pallor. Her abdomen is soft with mild left-sided tenderness on deep palpation; no palpable mass is identified on this visit.\n\n{patientName} is a retired schoolteacher who lives with her husband in a small apartment in Brno. She is close to her two adult children and enjoys tending her balcony garden and attending weekly choir rehearsals, though she has had to reduce these activities owing to fatigue. She does not smoke and drinks wine only occasionally. Her diet has historically been rich in red meat and low in fibre, consistent with traditional Czech cuisine. She is generally independent and motivated, though visibly anxious about her diagnosis.\n\nSymptom onset was insidious. {patientName} initially attributed the rectal bleeding and cramping to haemorrhoids and delayed seeking medical attention for nearly three months [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:1]. It was only after significant weight loss and persistent fatigue that her general practitioner referred her for colonoscopy. A colonoscopic biopsy confirmed adenocarcinoma of the colon, and subsequent imaging has been obtained to stage the disease [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:4].\n\n{patientName} has a supportive family network. Her daughter accompanies her to most appointments and helps manage her medications. She is motivated to continue treatment and asks detailed questions about each step of her care plan. She worries about being a burden on her family and about the side effects of chemotherapy. Psychosocial support and dietary counselling have been offered."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
